Business World: How To Execute 10%, Nicely
By Holman W. Jenkins Jr.

07/18/2001
The Wall Street Journal
A19
(Copyright (c) 2001, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.)

How come Ford adopts the same white-collar performance review system as=20
General Electric but gets vilified for it, hounded by discrimination lawyers=
=20
and AARP? Last week, less than a year after launching it, CEO Jacques Nasser=
=20
was moved to dump a brand new executive grading system designed to weed out=20
the least capable 10% of Ford's managers.=20
The short answer is that Ford isn't GE, though Jack Welch has been a model=20
for what Mr. Nasser seeks to accomplish at the auto company.
Bringing such a Torquemada system into a firm that faces slowing sales and=20
whose own boss considers his colleagues notoriously flabby and easy on=20
themselves meant it was a downsizing scheme from the start, whether=20
advertised that way or not. GE didn't introduce its version until a decade=20
after the Neutron Jack phase. But never mind. Trumpeting a win last week,=20
AARP declared its victory goes way beyond Ford. It sure does.=20
Forced ranking has waxed and waned as a fad over the decades, and most=20
students of management hold their noses around it. Its resurgence, at a time=
=20
when many employers are contemplating their first layoffs in years, can only=
=20
mean that companies are nervous about preserving their freedom to hire and=20
fire in a world run increasingly by the job-discrimination bar.=20
Ask any non-deluded European. What makes the U.S. economy relatively nimble=20
is that companies are not afraid to take on workers because they know they=20
can always get rid of them later. Harsh as this sounds, it's why we have a=20
lush job market compared to the employment Saharas of the Old World.=20
Yet firing in America has been a work in progress. Half a decade ago,=20
enlightened companies tried employee buyouts, but the lawyers descended,=20
forcing companies to offer the buyouts indiscriminately. Result: Highly=20
marketable workers took the windfall and immediately found other jobs, while=
=20
people who considered themselves unemployable skipped the loot and clung to=20
their cubicles.=20
Other companies, on the theory that it was OK to tell people they had to go=20
because their functions or departments were being discontinued, bravely=20
downsized the old-fashioned way. But this was no proof against lawsuits.=20
Remember Texaco, Coca-Cola and others where the very existence of=20
affirmative-action programs became fodder for litigation by both minorities=20
and older white employees?=20
Searching for a way out of the legal maze, Ford tried two years ago to=20
combine forced ranking with buyouts, aiming offers exclusively at low-ranked=
=20
employees. Result: grumbling in the hallways of "rewarding failure" and good=
=20
employees angling for low grades so they could become eligible for a golden=20
parachute. Finally, starting this year, Ford opted for an out-and-out forced=
=20
ranking system, which would have given 10% of white-collar employees annuall=
y=20
a "C" grade that meant either shape up or you're gone next year.=20
Microsoft, Lucent, Conoco, Enron and EDS all have used forced ranking to=20
maintain or improve the quality of their work forces. While many find the=20
idea distasteful or complain it substitutes a yearly spasm for what should b=
e=20
a continuous process, at least it solves a real problem. Survey after survey=
=20
finds that even the happiest worker-bees gripe about their employer's=20
reluctance to get strict with poor performers. A recent McKinsey poll of=20
managers at big companies found that only 16% said their employer could even=
=20
recognize the difference between stars and slackers.=20
But Ford was already in the soup over the Explorer/Firestone fiasco. It=20
didn't stand a chance when the Detroit papers opened a new front over its=20
A-B-C grading system for 18,000 managers. Accentuating the coverage was a=20
simmering quest to discover any sort of rift between Mr. Nasser and his=20
chairman, Bill Ford, great-grandson of the founder.=20
Mr. Ford has somehow been anointed keeper of the company's conscience becaus=
e=20
of blood chemistry or something. Inevitably, he wants to be liked and wants=20
the company to be liked. Putting a Ford in the chairmanship was probably the=
=20
worst thing the company could have done at a time when Mr. Nasser was clearl=
y=20
set on giving the place a kick in the pants.=20
In the ranking controversy, Mr. Ford soon was reported to be "concerned abou=
t=20
the system's impact on morale." Notice how this differs from "the system is=20
an urgent necessity so Ford can become a better company." With this kind of=20
support, management quickly wilted in the face of pressure from the old-folk=
s=20
lobby (which has appointed itself guardian of anybody over 45) and other=20
victim contingents.=20
Mr. Nasser didn't help himself by appearing in a Ford diversity video=20
haranguing an audience for containing "too many white faces" or by installin=
g=20
rewards for executives who meet minority hiring goals. Presto, lawsuits=20
galore. The ones Ford will have the most trouble with are those filed by=20
white males claiming they were victims of age discrimination in order to mak=
e=20
way for blacks and women.=20
One of the ironies, as Ford shows, is that companies these days have reasons=
=20
of their own for recruiting minorities and women. Were the supposedly=20
archaic, 19th-century principle of freedom of contract still in effect --=20
i.e., employers are free to hire and fire at will -- there would be a lot=20
more affirmative action, a lot more honestly pursued.=20
GE may not exactly be the rainbow coalition, but it does have a lesson for=20
Ford. Under its version of forced rankings, 10% of managers are assigned to =
a=20
bottom grade each year, which means they're cut off from the rich booty GE=20
awards the top 20% and the job security of the workaday 70%. If low-ranked=20
managers don't improve, they are asked to move on.=20
A big difference, though, is that the process is not concentrated in a=20
single, highly neuroticized annual ritual. GE carries on with much year-roun=
d=20
mentoring and bellowing and measuring, so nobody has cause to be surprised b=
y=20
the score he gets. In fact, anyone who went to work there in the past 15=20
years would have known exactly what he was getting into.=20
Here's the lesson: Nobody doubts that GE's hiring and firing, whatever the=20
color or gender of the fodder, is all about business. It takes time to build=
=20
a reputation for heartlessly focusing on the bottom line, but once you do, i=
t=20
can be liberating.

